@node unpack, route, pack, Keywords
@subsection Unpack
@table @asis
@item Syntax:
@code{Unpack <Call> [<offset> <matchcode>]1*}
@item Example:
@code{Unpack "mypack -e $a" 0e ffff????cefe}
@end table

This statement sets the call of certain unpackers according to a id in the
archiv file

call: see pack

offset: position of recognition string in packed file.

offset ::= <hexValue>

match code:  recognition string for packed file, ?? can be used as don't care

@example

e.g.: unpack "mypack -e %s" 0e ffff????cefe

       files packed by mypack can be recognized by
         ffff(hex) at offset 0e(hex) and
         cefe(hex) at offset 13(hex)
       they can be unpacked by "mypack -e <filename>"

@end example

@node route, routeFile, unpack, Keywords
@subsection route
@table @asis
@item Syntax:
@code{route <flavour> [enc|noenc] <target> @{<linkWW>@}}
@item Example:
@code{route crash 2:2433/1245 2:2433/* 2:2432/*}
@end table

This statement defines a route.

@strong{flavour:}
@enumerate
@item
hold
@item
normal
@item
crash
@item
direct
@item
immediate
@end enumerate

enc: means encrypted msgs

noenc: means unencrypted msgs

@strong{target:}
@enumerate
@item
<aka>
@item
host
@item
hub
@item
boss
@item
no-route
@end enumerate

linkWW is a dos pattern with ? and *.

Route statements are parsed in descending order:
Pseudo-code:

@example
  1) actual = first statement

  2) if linkWWW = msg-destination using pattern matching

  2a) take this routing and return

  2b) else actual = next statement

  3) jump to 2)
  
@end example

if no route statement found whose pattern matchs witch the aka, then the mail
is left alone.

